data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new **built-in span conversions**. The compiler now resolves `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. The `MemoryExtensions` overload cannot be represented in an expression tree, so it throws at runtime.

## Fix

Force the compiler to bind to the `Enumerable` overload by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `.Reverse()` on arrays (now binds to the in-place `Span` extension returning `void`). The same fix pattern applies — use `.AsEnumerable()` or call `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` explicitly.
